Matthew Tindal was an English jurist whose controversial writings on the freedom of the press, the relations of church and state, and the proper understanding of religion were extremely influential in the deist controversy of the early 18th century.
Tindal, the son of the Rev. John Tindal, an Anglican minister, studied law at Lincoln College, Oxford, and was elected fellow of All Souls College in 1678. Having embraced high church principles as a student, he joined the Roman Catholic Church in 1685. But in 1688, disillusioned with what he called “the absurdities of popery,” he returned to the Church of England.
Tindal’s work The Rights of the Christian Church Asserted, Against the Romish, and All other Priests (1706), published anonymously at first, argued for the subordination of the church to the state. The book was as popular as it was provocative, and in December of 1707, when it was already in its third edition, it was proscribed in a case brought against the author, the publisher, and a bookseller. Nevertheless, a fourth edition came out in 1709 and was promptly burned by order of the House of Commons.
Certain passages in a pastoral letter written by the Rev. Dr. Edward Gibson, Bishop of London appear to be a criticism of The Rights of the Christian Church. In particular, Gibson denounces “some late writings”—he leaves them unnamed—written under the “pretence of opposing the Encroachments of Popery, thereby to recommend himself to the unwary Protestant Reader.” This censure provoked two anonymously published replies from Tindal, An Address to the Inhabitants of London and Westminster, 2nd ed. (London: J. Peele, 1730) and A Second Address to the Inhabitants of the Two Great Cities of London and Westminster (London: J. Peele, 1730), in which he began to develop his critique of traditional Christianity. 
Tindal is best known for his work Christianity as Old as the Creation, vol. 1 (London: n.p., 1730), in which he brings together ideas from his Addresses in a sustained attack on revealed religion in general and Christianity in particular. He argues in this work that the religion of nature, known to everyone by internal light, is complete and clear, since God, who first gave it, is perfect and unchangeable; to suppose that it could be added to or altered would be to suppose a change in God. Tindal is more thorough than many of the previous deists in criticizing not only the doctrines but also the evidences of Christianity and the text of Scripture, which he represents as hopelessly obscure and of no use to the ordinary reader.

Thomas Sherlock (31 December 1677 - 17 July 1761) was an English divine who served as the Bishop of Bangor and Salisbury before taking the important position of the Bishop of London, which he held for 33 years.  Sherlock is known for his responses to Hoadly, Collins, and Woolston.
 
Sherlock was born in London in 1677.  He was the first son of Dr. William Sherlock, who was the dean of St. Paul’s Cathedral and master of the Temple Church.  Sherlock was educated at Eton, and entered St. Catharine’s Hall, Cambridge in 1693, where he earned his B.A, M.A., and D.D.  Subsequently Sherlock was made a fellow of his college and was also ordained in 1701. 
 
Following in his father’s footsteps, Sherlock was made master of the Temple after William Sherlock resigned, and was very well received there.  In subsequent years he made a name for himself as a preacher of great eminence.  Thus began his appointment to many positions, including: the Chaplin to the Queen, Prebendary of St. Paul’s Cathedral, Master of St. Catharine’s Hall and Vice-Chancellor of Cambridge, Canon of Norwich, Dean of Chichester, Bishop of Bangor, Bishop of Salisbury, Bishop of York, and Bishop of London.
 
Sherlock soon found himself in the middle of what was known as the Bangorian Controversy.  Originally initiated by the Bishop of Thetford, George Hickes, the controversy really took off when Sherlock’s fellow St. Catharine’s Hall graduate Benjamin Hoadly, the newly named Bishop of Bangor, threw his weight into fight, delivering a speech to King George I arguing church government is not something Christ instituted, and that the state should have authority over church matters.  Sherlock and a few others who were appointed to a committee to report on this situation, found themselves on opposite sides of the debate as the king, and Sherlock, along with others, lost their royal chaplaincies. 
 
His losses in one controversy did not cause him to shy away from taking on those he thought in error.  In 1725 he published a series of six sermons against the Deists in The Use and Intent of Prophecy, which saw many editions published.  A few years later, Sherlock again contributed to the fight against the Deists when he anonymously published his Tryal of the Witnesses of the Resurrection of Jesus in 1729, in opposition to Thomas Woolston’s Sixth Discourse.  The Tryal was popular, running through several editions in the first year alone.  Charles Moss wrote a defense of the Tryal against Peter Annet called The Evidence of the Resurrection Cleared From the Exception of a late Pamphlet (1744), that was later revised by Sherlock, re-titled the Sequel of the Tryal of the Witnesses, and republished in 1749.  Later, his Pastoral Letter sold thousands of copies in a matter of days.
 
Sherlock never seemed to relent, tirelessly defending his beliefs against a number of attacks, and yet found the time to perform his duties with excellence, and was well liked by many.  After what seems to have been a stroke in 1753, Sherlock continued to write and publish until his death in July of 1761.

Peter Annet (1693 – 18 January 1769) was an English schoolmaster and deist whose polemical writings against Christianity were early precursors for the aggressive populist writers of the revolutionary period like Thomas Paine.
 
Annet is said to have been born in Liverpool, and he supported himself for some time as a schoolmaster. But his violent published attacks on the apologetic works of Thomas Sherlock brought him into notoriety, and probably due to his lack of discretion he lost one teaching position some time in the mid 1740s. It is not altogether clear how he supported himself over the subsequent decades, though at some point he apparently held a minor government post. He was an active member of the Robin Hood Society, originally called “The Societie for Free and Candyd Enquirie,” a group consisting largely of freethinkers who met in a pub to debate religious and political questions.
 
Annet was a prolific writer of pamphlets and polemical books, publishing many of them anonymously or under a pseudonym. His forcible style and irreverent handling of everything he deemed ridiculous commended his ideas more to skeptical members of the working classes than to the more educated segment of the population. In 1739 he published a brief pamphlet containing two of his lectures against Christianity, and by the mid-1740s he was deeply entangled in anti-Christian polemics. His professed position, however, was not atheism; he maintained (following Tindal) that “the religion essential to man, the true original religion of nature and reason,” to which revelation could add nothing, teaches the existence of God, the need for repentance for sin, and the certainty of a future state of rewards and punishments – a religion practiced by Socrates and other illustrious ancients (Deism Fairly Stated, 5).
 
In 1763, Annet was brought to court at the King’s Bench on an accusation of blasphemous libel for the publication of several numbers of the short-lived freethinking paper The Free Enquirer (1761). The seventy year old Annet pled guilty and threw himself on the mercy of the court. In view of his age, he was sentenced to suffer one month’s confinement in Newgate (time already served), to stand twice in the pillory with a paper on his forehead inscribed “blasphemy,” to be confined in Bridewell to hard labor for one year, and to find security for his good behavior for the remainder of his life (Starkie, 140-41; Levy, 321-22). After his release, he kept a small school in Lambeth.
 
Annet’s first major contribution to the deist controversy was his book The Resurrection of Jesus Considered (1744), an attack on Thomas Sherlock’s Tryal of the Witnesses of the Resurrection (1729). Sherlock was himself responding to Thomas Woolston’s Sixth Discourse on the Miracles of Our Savoiur (1729), and in Annet’s judgment, Woolston had conceded too much, needlessly giving Sherlock premises for his positive argument. Annet argues chiefly for three points: that Jesus did not in fact foretell his resurrection either to the Jewish rulers or to his own disciples, that the story in Matthew of the watch set on Jesus’ tomb is incredible and absurd, and that the accounts given by the four evangelists of Jesus’ resurrection contradict each other at every point.
 
Every miracle, Annet writes, “is an absurdity to common sense and understanding, and contrary to the attributes of God” (64). And if an alleged event is “contradictory to the constant course of nature,” then even an eyewitness of it would have reason to doubt the veracity of his own eyesight; so much more, then, the should he doubt the judgment or veracity of those who report it to him at second hand (89).
 
Many of Annet’s arguments in this work were not new, but his vigorous and sarcastic manner of stating his points caught the attention of both Anglican and dissenting ministers. The most noteworthy replies were those by Chandler, Jackson, and Moss, all of whom are summarized in Leland (1754). Annet responded, Chandler rejoined, and the controversy eventually burned itself out.

Annet’s other major work, Deism Fairly Stated and Fully Vindicated (1746), was provoked by George Benson’s Reasonableness of the Christian Religion (1743), which was itself an answer to Henry Dodwell, Jr., Christianity Not Founded on Argument (1742). The book, which according to Leland was revised by Thomas Chubb before going to print (Leland, **), shows the influence of Tindal on Annet’s thought, both in its positive articulation of the sufficiency of deism for the religious needs of man and in its handling of the attack on miracles and prophecy by undermining the credibility of the Christian scriptures. Traditional reports of miracles and prophecy, Annet argues, do not prove that those reports themselves are written by the people whose names they bear, or that they are divinely inspired so as to be free from error, or that they have been faithfully transmitted and properly transmitted down through the ages to us (26). And if miraculous evidence for these points is not forthcoming, it is not reasonable to take these reports to be infallible truths; for the Protestants and Catholics cannot agree even as to which books belong in the canon (18-20). Annet rejects the doctrine of the atonement as absurd and repugnant to reason (41), dismisses the idea of the incarnation as unworthy of God (66-67), and insists that a divine revelation must be perfectly perspicuous in every part or else it is no revelation at all (83-87). Finally, he argues that if Christianity really were a divinely appointed religion, it should have been universally spread and received in all ages and all nations (89-90).

summary: Torrey was born in Hoboken, New Jersey, on 28 January 1856. He graduated from Yale University in 1875 and Yale Divinity School in 1878. Following graduation, Torrey became a Congregational minister in Garrettsville, Ohio, in 1878. The following year he married Clara Smith, and the Torreys had five children. After further studies in theology at Leipzig University and Erlangen University in 1882?1883, Torrey joined Dwight L. Moody in his evangelistic work in Chicago in 1889, and became superintendent of the Bible Institute of the Chicago Evangelization Society (now Moody Bible Institute). Five years later, he became pastor of the Chicago Avenue Church (now The Moody Church) in 1894.

Charles Moss (January 1712 - 12 April 1802) was an Anglican Bishop, first of St. David’s and later at Bath and Wells, and wrote a response to an attack on Sherlock’s Tryal of the Witnesses.
 
Moss was born to William and Sarah Moss, who owned a farm in Postwick, Norfolk, England.  Moss was baptized on the 3rd of January, 1712, and so was born in either late 1711 or early 1712.[i]  He entered Caius College, Cambridge in 1727 and received his B.A. and M.A. from that school, and also received a fellowship there. 
 
Moss, with the help of Thomas Sherlock, was able to secure a position as a Chaplin.  He rapidly moved up the ranks of the Church and became the Prebend of Warminster at Salisbury in 1738, then transferred to Hurstbourne and Burage in 1740.  In 1749 he was appointed Archdeacon of Colchester, and gained the livings of St. Andrew Undershaft, followed by St. James's, Piccadilly, and followed once again by St. George's, at Hanover Square.  In 1766 he was made the Bishop of St. David’s, and in 1774 was moved to Bath and Wells, where he remained Bishop until his death in 1802.
 
Moss was not a powerhouse of publication, however he did bring forth one major contribution, that of his work called, The Evidence of the Resurrection Cleared From the Exceptions of a late Pamphlet.  This work was written in defense of Bishop Sherlock’s Tryal of the Witnesses against the arguments Peter Annet anonymously published in his work The Resurrection of Jesus Considered.  In 1749Moss’s work was revised by Sherlock, though much of it remains the same, and republished as the Sequel to the Tryal of the Witnesses.  Additionally, Moss gave the Boyle Lectures for four consecutive years between 1759 and 1762, however, these lectures were never published.

Thomas Woolston (1670 - 26 January 1731) was a freethinker and controversial author who provoked a number of responses, chiefly against his Six Discourses on the Miracles of Our Saviour, at first published separately, and later bound into one volume. 

Woolston was born in early 1670 to a Northhampton tradesman, Henry Woolston.   In 1685 he entered Sidney-Sussex College at Cambridge where he earned his B.A., M.A., and eventually B.D. in 1699.  He received a fellowship from the college and remained there for some years.

During his studies, through reading the work of the Church Father Origen, he became convinced that an allegorical interpretation of Scripture was the correct approach.  At first he used these ideas as arguments for the truth of Christianity.  He gave a talk at Cambridge on these ideas: The Old Apology for the Truth of the Christian Religion in 1705, but it wasn’t until he started producing minor publications with these ideas and calling out clergy in the early 1720s that he found himself in trouble, and consequently his fellowship was stripped from him.  This was not the last, or the worst, of the trouble he would find himself in.

Woolston subsequently moved to London and proceeded to publish attacks on Anthony Collins in The Moderator Between an Infidel and an Apostate, published in 1725.  Woolston’s publications seemed to invite controversy and response from all sides, however it was his Six Discourses on the Miracles of Our Saviour that really ignited a firestorm of responses.  The first discourse was published 1727, as was the second, with the remaining four being published between 1728 and 1729.  The discourses proposed, as was consistent with his allegorical stance on the Gospels, that miracles could not be used as proof of the validity of Christianity, and denied, often with cutting remarks, the historicity of the miracles of the Biblical text.
In 1729 Woolston was brought to court on charges of blasphemy and was found guilty.  He was fined £25 for each of the first four Discourses and given a year in prison, but was unable to pay his fines and so remained in the King’s Bench Prison until his death in 1731.
